<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h1>Tutorial 10. Calculating and Cutting the Top Full Sweep Skirt and Full Underskirts.</h1>
<p>As I know from the calculations made during the previous tutorials, the part of the skirt showing from under the bodice should be 28cm long. I plan to sew a full gathered skirt and I prefer the gathers to start at the level of the bottom edge of the bodice. If I position the waistband of the skirt right at the waist level, the gathers will get wrinkled by the bodice. Instead of beautiful folds, I will get messy uneven tucks. Moreover, it will make the dress way too thick at the bottom of the bodice. <strong>Therefore, I prefer to make the waistband wider: for example, 4cm.</strong> And I will measure 28cm (skirt length) right down from the bottom edge of the bodice.</p>
<p><strong>Now, I need to determine its length as well. </strong>Noa’s stomach circumference measured 9cm below the waist was 73cm. With this in mind, <strong>I will make the waistband 70cm long </strong>(I can adjust the length after the fitting if the need comes).</p>
<p><strong>I also need to calculate the top full sweep skirt gathered at the waist. </strong></p>
<p>It should be a couple centimeters shorter than the underskirts so the ruffles show from underneath it nicely. Thus, if the skirt has a total length of 28cm and 2cm if left for the visible part of the ruffles, then <strong>the ready full sweep skirt should have a length of 26cm.</strong></p>
<p><strong>The waist will be gathered with a 2:1 ratio. </strong>In this case, I will do all calculations based on the assumption that <strong>the length of the top part of the skirt is 70cm x 2 = 140cm.</strong></p>
<p>I calculate the radius of the waist opening (or the top circumference of the skirt) following the formula: <strong>2πR = 140cm. R = 22cm. </strong>I remove 1cm (seam allowance) and get <strong>a radius of 21cm.</strong></p>
<p>The length of the ready skirt is 26cm plus 1cm for folding the hem. In other words, <strong>I need to cut a 27cm long skirt piece. </strong></p>
<p>The total radius for cutting out the skirt is as follows: <strong>R = 21 + 27 = 48cm. </strong></p>
<p>The fabric for cutting the skirt needs to have the following length: <strong>48cm х 2 = 96cm.</strong> It follows that <strong>the skirt fits into a square lay with a side length of 1m </strong>where the waist radius is 21cm and the total radius is 48cm of which 47cm is the length of the skirt. Therefore, fabric with a width of 150cm allows me to cut my full sweep skirt as a single seamless circle.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image002.jpg" alt="1 v:shapes="></p>
<p><strong>I fold the fabric in a square with a side length of 1m: </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p>Then, <strong>I fold it in a cone, </strong>secure with pins, and mark the total radius of 48cm of which 21cm is the waist opening and 27cm is the length of the skirt. I secure the lay with pins and cut along.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The result is a fabric circle which I fold in half:&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I mark the length of the zipper. You can make a dart or a regular slit. As for me, I do the latter. </strong>The fabric has a very bright print and the seam at the back will be absolutely unnoticeable.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I notch the skirt at the sides and in the middle:&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>These notches will be very helpful when I start sewing the skirt and distributing the folds: </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Now I will calculate the tiered underskirt.&nbsp; </strong></p>
<p><strong>The total length of the skirt is 28cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The skirt will be made of four tiers </strong>with a width of 10cm, 8cm, 6cm, and 4cm correspondingly. The last tier will be a two-layer chiffon ruffle.</p>
<p><strong>Let us calculate the length of the stripe for each tier. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Tier 1 </strong>will be made of a single 150cm long strip of fabric. This corresponds with the full width of my fabric. This 1.5m of fabric will have to be gathered down to 70cm.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 2 </strong>should be two times longer than the first tier – 3m. I will use two 150cm long stripes of fabric.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 3</strong> should be two times longer than the second tier – 6m. I will use four 150cm long stripes of fabric.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 4</strong> is a chiffon ruffle. It should be two times longer than the third tier – 12m. It will be made of eight 150cm long stripes of fabric.</p>
<p><strong>Now, let me calculate the width of each stripe of fabric. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Tier 1</strong> should have a width of 10cm when finished. I add 2.5cm for the seam allowances and get a total of 12.5cm – this is the width of the stripe of fabric used for the first tier. This tier will be cut from bright print fabric.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 2</strong> should have a width of 8cm when finished. I add 2.5cm for the seam allowances and get a total of 10.5cm – this is the width of the stripe of fabric used for the second tier. This tier will also be cut from motley fabric.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 3 </strong>should have a width of 6cm when finished. I add 2.5cm for the seam allowances and get a total of 8.5cm – this is the width of the stripe of fabric used for the third tier. This tier will be cut from yellow fabric.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 4 </strong>is a stripe of chiffon folded in half. The width of this tier is 4cm. 4cm plus another 4cm (because it will be folded) and plus 2.5cm for the seam allowances. As the result, the stripe for cutting the fourth tier should have a width of 10.5cm. This tier will be cut from yellow chiffon.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I will sew two such skirts to make the skirt fuller.</strong> Therefore, all pieces need to be cut out in pairs.</p>
<p><strong>In order to cut two identical skirts, I will need: </strong>2 stripes of fabric for the first tier, 4 stripes for the second tier, 8 stripes for the third tier, and 16 stripes with a width of 10.5cm for the fourth tier.</p>
<p><strong>I have prepared strips of fabric according to the calculations: </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Fancy%20Dresses%20for%20girls/12%20yo/Tutorial%2010.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p>It is very simple. All you need to do is prepare the right number of strips and double-check their widths.&nbsp;&nbsp; I have used the decorative print fabric, the fabric used for the bodice, and the chiffon.</p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
